review_blob:
Pours a surprising medium amber color, with a nose of clean malt and dark fruits. A full mouthfeel, this beer boasts a significant punch of dark fruits (raisin, plum, etc) all atop a caramel nut malt backbone. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Pours a ruddy brown. Strong plum, dark fruit aroma with matching flavor. Touch of munich malt in the background, but subsumed by strong dark caramel malts (120/special B). Would liked to have tasted more bready malt, less caramel--a bit cloying for a dopplebock.

Bottle. Expectations were high considering the North Coast label. Aroma was typical english hop (spicy, herbal) mixed with a sweet malt profile. Flavor well balanced with sweet malts followed by a heavy bittering--almost English IPA-esque (nice surprise) tart finish as well. Overall, nice balanced session ale.

I respect their decision to create a Fuggle IPA. However, I do miss those tangerines and grapefruits found in most U.S. IPAs. I wasnt impressed much with the aroma--while there were traces of fuggles, both sweet and woodsy--however, not as pronounced as other reviewers are describing. There were fruity notes from an interesting yeast strand. Nice balanced flavor with hop bitterness throughout mixed with a simple malt profile that fades in the background. Late finish of grassy and wood notes from the hops. Nice medium mouthfeel and a crisp, dry finish indeed. Overall--wouldnt put it on the "must try" list, but again, I appreciate the bold choice and variety.

Pours a dark, black-ruby body with a tan, creamy head that hangs around for a while before digressing to a thin rim. The smell is strong coffee, chocolate, and a touch of oak. The flavor is a nice array of coffee, chocolate malt, and sweet milk sugar. The mouthfeel is the creamiest Ive had in stout--like whole milk going down. Very little bittering leaves the sweetness to ring out finishing soft and sweet.

Overall, great commercial porter. Pours nice and dark--mahogany/black with a nice  head.  Aroma is chocolate, roasted malt, and some sweetness. Flavor is balanced nicely with great malt, a clean yeast throughout, followed by a chocolate malt bitterness. Bitter finish is well pronounced and dies rather quickly. Nice creamy mouthfeel as well. Great porter.

A hazy golden pour with a nice head. The aroma is mainly wheat with banana and citrus notes. The flavor matches the aroma with a strong wheat flavor and banana throughout; some clove notes as well--the finish is quite sour for this style. The carbonation is soft and complements the smooth taste. Overall, one of the better wheat beers around--great for summer.

Beautiful orange/amber pour with a nice thin white head. Aroma isnt much to write home about--some citrus hops, but faint. Flavor is exceptionally smooth, balanced, and mild. I was expecting more pronounced hops throughout. Malt is nice--but very simple. Finish is not as bitter as most IPAs. Overall, quite drinkable and smooth, but not an IPA exemplar.

Golden color, white head. Favor has straw, cereal, light malt. Nice carbonation.
No apologies--this beer is the best of the American macros.
The aroma and flavor of this american wheat beer is not too shabby. More wheat aroma and fllavor than most--overall a great summer ale.

A motor oil, dark black pour--the darkest ive seen; nice thick creamy tan head that hangs around the whole time. The aroma is a nice roasted malt with coffee, carmamel and some sweetness. The flavor is a nice balance of ashy roasted malts, and sweet, sticky burnt sugar. The finish is a strong burnt malt with an alcohol warming. Palate is chewy and appropriate given the flavor. Carbonation is a touch too much, but nothing a little swirling of the glass cant fix. One of the best american imperials stouts around!
beer_name: North Coast Old Rasputin Russian Imperial Stout

review_blob: Dont be fooled by my rating. There are those occasions when only a PBR will do.

As a disclaimer, I must say--Fat Tire is in a class by itself. I have never had a beer quite like this. The pour is amber/orange with a creamy white head that hangs around for a while. The aroma is more nutty, toasty, and biscuity than anything I have ever tried. With the flavor, there is no surprises--cereal, nutty, biscuity malt throughout--great moderate carbonation, and very little hop presence. While this is not one of the greatest beers around--its a great Miller Light substitute during a night of darts!
A true American Classic. This lightly hopped ale is balanced perfectly with its butterscotch malt. Smooth and refreshing--Its an American Macro that I can stand behind.

[12oz Bottle] Dark, mahogany brown with an off-white creamy head--great retention. Aroma consists mainly of roasted malt, some chocolate and coffee.
Flavor is well-balanced throughout! There is a nice blend of front hop notes (acidic) with a caramel, malty body. The clean yeast comes through on this one nicely. Malt is predominantly roasty--and hops, though faintly, are detected throughout; alcohol presence near the end. Palate is more thin than I would expect and flavors dissipate rather quickly. Im not a huge brown ale fan--but this one keeps it interesting enough for me.

Pours a dark brown black with very little head. Nose was mocha, very fruity plum, fig, some alcohol. Flavor--nice fruit with hints of ash throughout--alcohol a bit too noticeable for a 7%. Burnt malt finish--well balanced all together. Carbonation moderate; mouthfeel a bit thin. Does not quite fit the Impy stout guidelines, but not too broken-hearted about it. Overall, a great drinkable, well balanced, fruity stout.

Did I have the same beer? I must say, my expectations were high, but I was sorely dissapointed with this IPA. It poured a shade darker than a filtered American lager--crystal clear and golden.  Aroma was overwhelmingly citrus/tangerine (from the Amarillo, no doubt). A clean yeast and some slight wood notes also came through. The flavor matched the aroma with a thin mouthfeel and overpowering tangerine hop--some spice and soapiness also. The beer finishes with mainly citrus hop--not very bitter--fades quickly. Overall, this IPA seemed quite dry and overwhelmingly citric--would like to have tasted a more complex hop bill.

Pours a strong cloudy orange with a white creamy head--average lacing. Aroma mainly malt, nutty notes; some citrus hops as well. Flavor was strong malt for a pale ale--and much appreciated. Some citrus/tangerine malts come through up front then fade quickly to a lasting, strong bittering finish. Nice balance. Extremely drinkable--great pale ale!

This beer pours a thick black motor oil with a dark tan head that fades quickly. The aroma is strong consisting of piney and citrus hops, big roasted malt, some chocolate, a few sugars, wood, and chalky. First taste of this beer I noticed the hop presence right away; the hops along with a moderate to heavy carbonation detracts from the complex nutty, cofee, and caramel notes. I noticed few other sugar flavors (brown/cane?) as well. Alcohol presence is a bit harsh. Strong bittering finish from the hops (piney) that lasts a while. Did not expect such a strong hop profile in this imperial stout. I may need to think about this beer for a while and then try it again in a few months.

Pours a dark brown opaque body with medium tan head that sticks around like the creme from an espresso. Aroma is crazy sweet with chocolate malt and nuttiness--a touch of wood. Tastes insanely smooth and creamy; a ton of chocolate malt, complex sugars, and some coffee notes to round it out. Low carbonation allows for the complexities to come through unscathed. Minimal hop; and alcohol presence almost non-existent. A lasting bitterness that comes in late and stays for a while. One of the best beers I have had to date.

Pours a beautiful orange amber with a one inch off-white head. Aroma is a great balance of floral/herbal, citrus hops with a touch of caramal malt. Not as strong as it could be. Flavor is surprisingly balanced--great floral front hop (slight grapefruit--not too much), a complex nutty, caramel malt background, followed by a moderate bittering finish.  Not too bitter; not too sweet. Mouthfeel, for this size beer, is has a pleasant unexpected stickyness. I concur with many that this makes a great session IPA in an age of big beers.
UPDATED: AUG 14, 2007

The body is a deep, dark brown, with a tan head that collects around the edge of the glass. The aroma, while more sublte than most, is sweet, malty, (maybe) coffee, and a touch of wood. The flavor is slightly sour, but nice; there are notes of chocolate and caramel malts, with a strong carbonation. The hops are more evident than expected--but overall nice. The mouthfeel is quite creamy--exceptional!  Yeast esters add to the complexity. Lasting finish from both the roasted malt and hops.

This beer pours a dark plum, brown with a fruity nose that will set you somewhere between candyland and Willy Wonka. Intense plums, figs, and raisins erupt onto the palate all the while accompanied by a stong carbonation. A pleasant bittering finish neutralizes and blances this complex "still-not-sure-what-hit-you" ale!

This pours a dark cocoa, black ink with a tan creamy head. Aroma consists of a touch of oak and smoke. Overwhelming flavors of bakers chocolate pair well with the sweetness of the crystal malt. The clean Engish ale yeast cuts through mid-way with a lasting bitterness that hangs around for a few minutes.

I think this beer gets a bad rap. It pours a beautiful golden amber; nice bright fruity nose. The light carbonation complements the subtle malty, nutty and almost cherry flavors. Finishes dry with a tart turn at the end. Great summer-on-the-porch brew.
UPDATED: AUG 14, 2007
